    "content": "# Terraform on AWS\n\n    ## What it is\n    Terraform on AWS is Infrastructure as Code for AWS providers, resources, data sources, variables, outputs, state, backends, modules, workspaces, plan/apply/destroy. This note is written for interview preparation and production implementation, so it covers the service mental model, setup path, IAM/security, scaling, failure behavior, monitoring, and comparison with related services.\n\n    ## Why it exists\n    Terraform on AWS exists because production systems need a managed building block instead of re-implementing the same infrastructure repeatedly. The important interview skill is not only naming the service, but explaining the workload shape where it is the right tool and the workload shape where it becomes the wrong tool.\n\n    ## Mental model\n    Think of Terraform on AWS as a boundary in your architecture. It accepts input, applies its own rules and limits, integrates with IAM and CloudWatch, and then hands control to the next service or consumer. In design discussions, always identify producer, consumer, failure path, retry path, and monitoring signal.\n\n    ## Core concepts\n    | Concept | Production meaning |\n    |---|---|\n    | Provider | AWS plugin |\n| Resource | Managed object |\n| Data source | Read existing object |\n| Variable | Input |\n| Output | Exported value |\n| State | Terraform record |\n| Backend | State location |\n| Module | Reusable config |\n\n    ## Flow diagram\n    ```mermaid\n    flowchart TD\n  A[Write .tf] --> B[terraform init]\n  B --> C[terraform plan]\n  C --> D[Review]\n  D --> E[terraform apply]\n  E --> F[AWS resources]\n  F --> G[Remote state]\n    ```\n\n    ## Setup from console\n    1. Install Terraform/AWS CLI\n2. Configure IAM credentials/role\n3. Create S3 backend bucket\n4. Create DynamoDB lock table if used\n5. Write provider/resources\n6. terraform init\n7. terraform fmt/validate\n8. terraform plan\n9. terraform apply\n10. review state/outputs\n\n    ## CLI or SDK example\n    ```hcl\n    terraform {\n  backend \"s3\" {\n    bucket = \"company-terraform-state\"\n    key = \"prod/app.tfstate\"\n    region = \"ap-south-1\"\n    encrypt = true\n  }\n}\nprovider \"aws\" { region = var.aws_region }\n    ```\n\n    ## Security and IAM permissions\n    Use least privilege. Give the calling identity only the exact actions and resources it needs. For AWS services, prefer IAM roles over access keys. For cross-service invocation, remember that the caller may need an identity policy while the target may also need a resource policy. If encryption uses KMS, the KMS key policy must allow the same access path.\n\n    ## Networking and VPC considerations\n    Ask whether the service is public, private, VPC-attached, or accessed through endpoints. For private workloads, keep compute in private subnets, expose traffic through API Gateway or ALB, and restrict security groups to known callers.\n\n    ## Retry and failure behavior\n    Decide what happens when the downstream service fails. For event-driven flows, use retries, DLQs, idempotency keys, deterministic output paths, and failure records. For synchronous APIs, return clear status codes and avoid hiding long-running processing inside a single request.\n\n    ## Scaling behavior\n    Scaling depends on the service. Serverless services scale by managed concurrency/capacity, queues absorb bursts, databases scale around partition/index/connection limits, and containers scale by replicas/tasks/pods. Always include the bottleneck: database connections, hot partitions, queue age, target health, or worker runtime.\n\n    ## Monitoring and debugging\n    Use CloudWatch logs, metrics, alarms, and structured correlation IDs. Debug by verifying IAM permissions, event payload shape, region/account, resource ARNs, networking, KMS permissions, and target health.\n\n    ## Cost mental model\n    Cost usually comes from requests, storage, compute duration, data transfer, provisioned capacity, logs, and retries. Production designs should clean up old data, avoid noisy logs, and avoid retry storms.\n\n    ## Common mistakes\n    - Choosing Terraform on AWS because it is familiar rather than because the workload matches it.\n    - Forgetting IAM or resource-based permissions.\n    - Missing DLQ/retry/idempotency for async processing.\n    - Ignoring CloudWatch metrics until production fails.\n    - Putting large payloads in events instead of storing data in S3 and sending references.\n    - Not documenting when the service should not be used.\n\n    ## When to use\n    Use Terraform on AWS when its managed behavior matches the problem: durability, routing, queueing, orchestration, compute, relational querying, NoSQL access, ETL, or observability depending on the service.\n\n    ## When not to use\n    Do not use Terraform on AWS as a universal hammer. If you need strict relational joins, use RDS/Aurora. If you need durable work buffering, use SQS. If you need orchestration, use Step Functions. If you need long-running compute, use ECS/Glue/Batch instead of forcing Lambda.\n\n    ## Comparison with alternatives\n    Terraform vs CloudFormation vs CDK: Terraform is multi-provider declarative IaC; CloudFormation is AWS-native; CDK is code that synthesizes CloudFormation.\n\n    ## Interview explanation\n    In an interview, explain Terraform on AWS in four sentences: what it is, why it exists, the exact production scenario where you would use it, and the exact scenario where you would not use it. Then mention IAM, retry/failure path, monitoring, and cost.\n\n    ## State warning\nState is critical. Use remote state for teams. Do not edit Terraform-managed resources manually without importing/reconciling drift.\n\n    ## Production checklist\n    - Least-privilege IAM is defined.\n    - Encryption and secret handling are configured.\n    - Retry, DLQ, or failure destination exists where applicable.\n    - CloudWatch logs/metrics/alarms exist.\n    - Cost cleanup/lifecycle/retention is configured.\n    - Terraform or IaC exists for repeatability.\n    - Runbook exists for common failures.\n"
