    "content": "# TTL Caching\n\n    ## What it is\n    TTL Caching covers time-limited caching, stale data trade-offs, decorators, and side effects. The goal is to understand the concept well enough to implement it, debug it, and explain it in an interview.\n\n    ## Why it exists\n    It exists because real applications need predictable structure, maintainable code, clear boundaries, error handling, and production behavior rather than only happy-path snippets.\n\n    ## Mental model\n    ```mermaid\n    flowchart LR\n A[Call] --> B{Cache valid?}\n B -->|yes| C[Return cached]\n B -->|no| D[Compute and store]\n    ```\n\n    ## Core concepts\n    - Definition and role in the stack.\n    - Input/output boundary.\n    - Runtime behavior.\n    - Failure behavior.\n    - Common abstractions.\n    - Production trade-offs.\n\n    ## Practical example\n    ```python\n    import time\ncache = {}\ndef get_value(key):\n    value, expiry = cache.get(key, (None, 0))\n    if time.time() < expiry: return value\n    value = expensive_call(key); cache[key] = (value, time.time()+60); return value\n    ```\n\n    ## Common mistakes\n    - Mixing unrelated responsibilities.\n    - Handling only success path.\n    - Ignoring validation, errors, and cleanup.\n    - Not thinking about scale and observability.\n    - Memorizing syntax without mental model.\n\n    ## Production notes\n    Use clear project structure, consistent error shapes, logging, tests, environment config, and separation between transport layer, business logic, and persistence.\n\n    ## Interview explanation\n    Start with what it is, why it exists, how it works internally, then give a practical example and a production caveat.\n"
