    "content": "# FastAPI Fundamentals\n\n    ## What it is\n    FastAPI Fundamentals covers FastAPI backend development: fastapi fundamentals, ASGI lifecycle, validation, dependencies, auth, async, DB, microservices, and deployment. The goal is to understand the concept well enough to implement it, debug it, and explain it in an interview.\n\n    ## Why it exists\n    It exists because real applications need predictable structure, maintainable code, clear boundaries, error handling, and production behavior rather than only happy-path snippets.\n\n    ## Mental model\n    ```mermaid\n    flowchart TD\n A[Request] --> B[ASGI/Uvicorn]\n B --> C[Middleware]\n C --> D[Dependencies]\n D --> E[Pydantic validation]\n E --> F[Route]\n F --> G[Response model]\n    ```\n\n    ## Core concepts\n    - Definition and role in the stack.\n    - Input/output boundary.\n    - Runtime behavior.\n    - Failure behavior.\n    - Common abstractions.\n    - Production trade-offs.\n\n    ## Practical example\n    ```python\n    from fastapi import FastAPI, Depends, HTTPException\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\napp = FastAPI()\nclass ItemCreate(BaseModel):\n    name: str\n@app.post(\"/items\", status_code=201)\ndef create_item(payload: ItemCreate):\n    if not payload.name.strip():\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=400, detail=\"name is required\")\n    return {\"id\": 1, \"name\": payload.name}\n    ```\n\n    ## Common mistakes\n    - Mixing unrelated responsibilities.\n    - Handling only success path.\n    - Ignoring validation, errors, and cleanup.\n    - Not thinking about scale and observability.\n    - Memorizing syntax without mental model.\n\n    ## Production notes\n    Use clear project structure, consistent error shapes, logging, tests, environment config, and separation between transport layer, business logic, and persistence.\n\n    ## Interview explanation\n    Start with what it is, why it exists, how it works internally, then give a practical example and a production caveat.\n\n    ## FastAPI-specific depth\nCover ASGI, Uvicorn, Pydantic request/response models, Depends, middleware, BackgroundTasks, async vs sync routes, OAuth2/JWT, CORS, SQLAlchemy/Alembic, WebSockets, streaming, Docker, ECS/Kubernetes deployment, and React integration.\n"
