    "content": "# Redux Fundamentals\n\n    ## What it is\n    Redux Fundamentals covers Redux state management: redux fundamentals, predictable updates, async flows, and server-state caching. The goal is to understand the concept well enough to implement it, debug it, and explain it in an interview.\n\n    ## Why it exists\n    It exists because real applications need predictable structure, maintainable code, clear boundaries, error handling, and production behavior rather than only happy-path snippets.\n\n    ## Mental model\n    ```mermaid\n    flowchart LR\n A[Component] --> B[dispatch/hook]\n B --> C[Middleware/API]\n C --> D[Reducer/cache]\n D --> E[Selector]\n E --> A\n    ```\n\n    ## Core concepts\n    - Definition and role in the stack.\n    - Input/output boundary.\n    - Runtime behavior.\n    - Failure behavior.\n    - Common abstractions.\n    - Production trade-offs.\n\n    ## Practical example\n    ```jsx\n    import { createApi, fetchBaseQuery } from \"@reduxjs/toolkit/query/react\";\nexport const api = createApi({\n  reducerPath: \"api\",\n  baseQuery: fetchBaseQuery({ baseUrl: \"/api\" }),\n  tagTypes: [\"User\"],\n  endpoints: (builder) => ({\n    getUsers: builder.query({ query: () => \"/users\", providesTags: [\"User\"] })\n  })\n});\n    ```\n\n    ## Common mistakes\n    - Mixing unrelated responsibilities.\n    - Handling only success path.\n    - Ignoring validation, errors, and cleanup.\n    - Not thinking about scale and observability.\n    - Memorizing syntax without mental model.\n\n    ## Production notes\n    Use clear project structure, consistent error shapes, logging, tests, environment config, and separation between transport layer, business logic, and persistence.\n\n    ## Interview explanation\n    Start with what it is, why it exists, how it works internally, then give a practical example and a production caveat.\n\n    ## Redux-specific depth\nCover store, actions, reducers, selectors, middleware, Redux Toolkit, Immer, createSlice, createAsyncThunk, RTK Query, tags, invalidation, optimistic updates, normalized state, DevTools, and Redux vs Context.\n"
